-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- JOHN CHAPTER 7 — The Feast of Tabernacles and the Rivers of Living Water
-- 53 verses · Greek text · Word studies · Cross-refs
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- Step 1: Insert chapter metadata
INSERT INTO chapters (book_id, chapter_number, overview, theme, key_word_original, key_word_meaning, outline)
SELECT b.id, 7,
  'John 7 takes place at the Feast of Tabernacles (Sukkot), six months after the events of chapter 6. The chapter is a study in division: the crowd is divided about Jesus, the authorities are divided over whether to arrest him, and even his own brothers do not believe in him. Jesus initially refuses to go up to the feast publicly — ''My time is not yet come'' (v.6) — but then goes ''not openly, but as it were in secret'' (v.10). Once there, he teaches in the temple and the people are amazed: ''How knoweth this man letters, having never learned?'' (v.15). Jesus responds that his doctrine comes from the Father: ''My doctrine is not mine, but his that sent me'' (v.16). He challenges his critics: ''Did not Moses give you the law, and yet none of you keepeth the law? Why go ye about to kill me?'' (v.19). The crowd is sharply divided: ''Some said, He is a good man: others said, Nay; but he deceiveth the people'' (v.12). Some recognise him as ''the Prophet'' or ''the Christ,'' while others object that ''the Christ cometh not out of Galilee'' (vv.40-42). On the last great day of the feast, Jesus stands and cries with a loud voice: ''If any man thirst, let him come unto me, and drink. He that believeth on me, as the scripture hath said, out of his belly shall flow rivers of living water'' (vv.37-38). John explains that this refers to the Holy Spirit, ''which they that believe on him should receive'' (v.39). The Pharisees send officers to arrest Jesus, but the officers return empty-handed: ''Never man spake like this man'' (v.46). Nicodemus, who had come to Jesus by night (ch.3), speaks cautiously in Jesus'' defence: ''Doth our law judge any man, before it hear him?'' (v.51). The chapter ends with the authorities'' dismissive retort and everyone going home.',
  'The Feast of Tabernacles — Division over the Christ',
  'διχάζω / σχίσμα (dichazō / schisma)',
  'To divide, separate / a split, division, tear. John 7 is the chapter of schisma — the people are divided (v.12, 43), the authorities are divided (vv.45-52), and even Jesus'' family is divided (vv.3-5). The feast of Tabernacles celebrated Israel''s wilderness wandering (Leviticus 23:33-43) with water-pouring ceremonies and light illumination — both of which Jesus claims to fulfil: ''If any man thirst, let him come unto me'' (7:37) and ''I am the light of the world'' (8:12). Every person who encounters Jesus must take a position — neutrality is impossible.',
  '["Jesus and His Brothers (vv.1-9): After these things Jesus walked in Galilee for he would not walk in Jewry because the Jews sought to kill him. Now the Jews'' feast of tabernacles was at hand. His brethren therefore said unto him Depart hence and go into Judaea that thy disciples also may see the works that thou doest. For there is no man that doeth any thing in secret and he himself seeketh to be known openly. If thou do these things shew thyself to the world. For neither did his brethren believe in him. Then Jesus said unto them My time is not yet come but your time is alway ready. The world cannot hate you but me it hateth because I testify of it that the works thereof are evil. Go ye up unto this feast I go not up yet unto this feast for my time is not yet full come. When he had said these words he abode still in Galilee","Jesus at the Feast — Secret Arrival and Public Teaching (vv.10-24): But when his brethren were gone up then went he also up unto the feast not openly but as it were in secret. Then the Jews sought him at the feast and said Where is he? And there was much murmuring among the people concerning him for some said He is a good man others said Nay but he deceiveth the people. Howbeit no man spake openly of him for fear of the Jews. Now about the midst of the feast Jesus went up into the temple and taught. And the Jews marvelled saying How knoweth this man letters having never learned? Jesus answered them and said My doctrine is not mine but his that sent me. If any man will do his will he shall know of the doctrine whether it be of God or whether I speak of myself. He that speaketh of himself seeketh his own glory but he that seeketh his glory that sent him the same is true and no unrighteousness is in him. Did not Moses give you the law and yet none of you keepeth the law? Why go ye about to kill me? The people answered and said Thou hast a devil who goeth about to kill thee? Jesus answered and said unto them I have done one work and ye all marvel. Moses therefore gave unto you circumcision — not because it is of Moses but of the fathers — and ye on the sabbath day circumcise a man. If a man on the sabbath day receive circumcision that the law of Moses should not be broken are ye angry at me because I have made a man every whit whole on the sabbath day? Judge not according to the appearance but judge righteous judgment","Is This the Christ? Division Among the People (vv.25-36): Then said some of them of Jerusalem Is not this he whom they seek to kill? But lo he speaketh boldly and they say nothing unto him. Do the rulers know indeed that this is the very Christ? Howbeit we know this man whence he is but when Christ cometh no man knoweth whence he is. Then cried Jesus in the temple as he taught saying Ye both know me and ye know whence I am and I am not come of myself but he that sent me is true whom ye know not. But I know him for I am from him and he hath sent me. Then they sought to take him but no man laid hands on him because his hour was not yet come. And many of the people believed on him and said When Christ cometh will he do more miracles than these which this man hath done? The Pharisees heard that the people murmured such things concerning him and the Pharisees and the chief priests sent officers to take him. Then said Jesus Yet a little while am I with you and then I go unto him that sent me. Ye shall seek me and shall not find me and where I am thither ye cannot come. Then said the Jews among themselves Whither will he go that we shall not find him? will he go unto the dispersed among the Gentiles and teach the Gentiles? What manner of saying is this that he said Ye shall seek me and shall not find me and where I am thither ye cannot come?","Rivers of Living Water (vv.37-39): In the last day that great day of the feast Jesus stood and cried saying If any man thirst let him come unto me and drink. He that believeth on me as the scripture hath said out of his belly shall flow rivers of living water. But this spake he of the Spirit which they that believe on him should receive for the Holy Ghost was not yet given because that Jesus was not yet glorified","Division and Failed Arrest (vv.40-53): Many of the people therefore when they heard this saying said Of a truth this is the Prophet. Others said This is the Christ. But some said Shall Christ come out of Galilee? Hath not the scripture said That Christ cometh of the seed of David and out of the town of Bethlehem where David was? So there was a division among the people because of him. And some of them would have taken him but no man laid hands on him. Then came the officers to the chief priests and Pharisees and they said unto them Why have ye not brought him? The officers answered Never man spake like this man. Then answered them the Pharisees Are ye also deceived? Have any of the rulers or of the Pharisees believed on him? But this people who knoweth not the law are cursed. Nicodemus saith unto them — he that came to Jesus by night being one of them — Doth our law judge any man before it hear him and know what he doeth? They answered and said unto him Art thou also of Galilee? Search and look for out of Galilee ariseth no prophet. And every man went unto his own house"]'
FROM books b WHERE b.name = 'John';

-- Step 2: Insert all 53 verses
INSERT INTO verses (chapter_id, verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
SELECT c.id, v.verse_number, v.kjv_text, v.original_text, v.transliteration, v.study_note, v.doctrinal_note
FROM chapters c
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (1, 'After these things Jesus walked in Galilee: for he would not walk in Jewry, because the Jews sought to kill him.',
   'καὶ μετὰ ταῦτα περιεπάτει ὁ Ἰησοῦς ἐν τῇ Γαλιλαίᾳ οὐ γὰρ ἤθελεν ἐν τῇ Ἰουδαίᾳ περιπατεῖν ὅτι ἐζήτουν αὐτὸν οἱ Ἰουδαῖοι ἀποκτεῖναι',
   'kai meta tauta periepatei ho Iēsous en tē Galilaia ou gar ēthelen en tē Ioudaia peripatein hoti ezētoun auton hoi Ioudaioi apokteinai',
   '''After these things'' — a gap of approximately six months between chapters 6 (near Passover, spring) and 7 (Feast of Tabernacles, autumn). ''Would not walk in Jewry'' (ouk ēthelen en tē Ioudaia peripatein — he did not wish to travel in Judea). Not fear but strategic timing: Jesus controls his own schedule (cf. v.6, 8, 30). ''The Jews sought to kill him'' — the plot from 5:18 continues.',
   NULL),
  (2, 'Now the Jews'' feast of tabernacles was at hand.',
   'ἦν δὲ ἐγγὺς ἡ ἑορτὴ τῶν Ἰουδαίων ἡ σκηνοπηγία',
   'ēn de engys hē heortē tōn Ioudaiōn hē skēnopēgia',
   '''Feast of tabernacles'' (hē skēnopēgia — the feast of tent-pitching, booth-building). Sukkot was one of three pilgrim feasts (Deuteronomy 16:16) celebrating the completed harvest and remembering Israel''s 40-year wilderness wandering. It lasted seven days (Leviticus 23:34-36) with an eighth day of solemn assembly. Key ceremonies included water-pouring (from the Pool of Siloam onto the altar) and lighting of enormous candelabra in the Court of Women. Both ceremonies provide the backdrop for Jesus'' claims in 7:37-38 and 8:12.',
   NULL),
  (3, 'His brethren therefore said unto him, Depart hence, and go into Judaea, that thy disciples also may see the works that thou doest.',
   'εἶπον οὖν πρὸς αὐτὸν οἱ ἀδελφοὶ αὐτοῦ Μετάβηθι ἐντεῦθεν καὶ ὕπαγε εἰς τὴν Ἰουδαίαν ἵνα καὶ οἱ μαθηταί σου θεωρήσωσιν τὰ ἔργα σου ἃ ποιεῖς',
   'eipon oun pros auton hoi adelphoi autou Metabēthi enteuthen kai hypage eis tēn Ioudaian hina kai hoi mathētai sou theōrēsousin ta erga sou ha poieis',
   '''His brethren'' (hoi adelphoi autou — his brothers). These are Jesus'' biological half-brothers: James, Joses, Simon, and Judas (Matthew 13:55). Their advice is worldly wisdom: go to Jerusalem where the crowds are, display your powers, build your platform. They think in terms of publicity and political strategy — the opposite of Jesus'' approach.',
   NULL),
  (4, 'For there is no man that doeth any thing in secret, and he himself seeketh to be known openly. If thou do these things, shew thyself to the world.',
   'οὐδεὶς γὰρ ἐν κρυπτῷ τι ποιεῖ καὶ ζητεῖ αὐτὸς ἐν παρρησίᾳ εἶναι εἰ ταῦτα ποιεῖς φανέρωσον σεαυτὸν τῷ κόσμῳ',
   'oudeis gar en kryptō ti poiei kai zētei autos en parrēsia einai ei tauta poieis phanerōson seauton tō kosmō',
   '''In secret... known openly'' (en kryptō... en parrēsia — in hiding vs. in public boldness). ''Show thyself to the world'' (phanerōson seauton tō kosmō — manifest, reveal yourself to the world). The brothers'' logic is worldly: if you have power, use it for maximum publicity. This echoes Satan''s temptation (Matthew 4:5-6: throw yourself from the temple). Jesus will indeed manifest himself — but on the cross, not on a stage.',
   NULL),
  (5, 'For neither did his brethren believe in him.',
   'οὐδὲ γὰρ οἱ ἀδελφοὶ αὐτοῦ ἐπίστευον εἰς αὐτόν',
   'oude gar hoi adelphoi autou episteuon eis auton',
   '''Neither did his brethren believe in him'' (oude hoi adelphoi autou episteuon eis auton — not even his brothers believed in him; imperfect tense: they were not believing, a sustained state of unbelief). This is remarkable: those who grew up with Jesus did not believe. Familiarity bred scepticism rather than faith. Their conversion came later — after the resurrection (Acts 1:14; 1 Corinthians 15:7). James became the leader of the Jerusalem church (Acts 15:13; Galatians 1:19) and Jude wrote the epistle.',
   NULL),
  (6, 'Then Jesus said unto them, My time is not yet come: but your time is alway ready.',
   'λέγει οὖν αὐτοῖς ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ὁ καιρὸς ὁ ἐμὸς οὔπω πάρεστιν ὁ δὲ καιρὸς ὁ ὑμέτερος πάντοτέ ἐστιν ἕτοιμος',
   'legei oun autois ho Iēsous Ho kairos ho emos oupō parestin ho de kairos ho hymeteros pantote estin hetoimos',
   '''My time'' (ho kairos ho emos — my appointed season, my opportune moment). ''Not yet come'' (oupō parestin — has not yet arrived). Jesus operates on a divine timetable, not a human one. ''Your time is alway ready'' (ho kairos ho hymeteros pantote estin hetoimos — your time is always ready) — for the unbelieving brothers, any moment is as good as any other because they have no divine commission with a set schedule. Jesus lives under the Father''s sovereign timing; they live under their own.',
   NULL),
  (7, 'The world cannot hate you; but me it hateth, because I testify of it, that the works thereof are evil.',
   'οὐ δύναται ὁ κόσμος μισεῖν ὑμᾶς ἐμὲ δὲ μισεῖ ὅτι ἐγὼ μαρτυρῶ περὶ αὐτοῦ ὅτι τὰ ἔργα αὐτοῦ πονηρά ἐστιν',
   'ou dynatai ho kosmos misein hymas eme de misei hoti egō martyrō peri autou hoti ta erga autou ponēra estin',
   '''The world cannot hate you'' — because the brothers belong to the world''s value system, the world has no reason to oppose them. ''Me it hateth'' (eme de misei — but me it hates). ''Because I testify of it, that the works thereof are evil'' — Jesus'' testimony exposes the world''s evil, and the world hates the light that reveals its darkness (cf. 3:19-20). The world''s hatred of Jesus is not random but moral: it is the reaction of evil exposed by good.',
   NULL),
  (8, 'Go ye up unto this feast: I go not up yet unto this feast; for my time is not yet full come.',
   'ὑμεῖς ἀνάβητε εἰς τὴν ἑορτὴν ταύτην ἐγὼ οὔπω ἀναβαίνω εἰς τὴν ἑορτὴν ταύτην ὅτι ὁ καιρὸς ὁ ἐμὸς οὔπω πεπλήρωται',
   'hymeis anabēte eis tēn heortēn tautēn egō oupō anabainō eis tēn heortēn tautēn hoti ho kairos ho emos oupō peplērōtai',
   '''I go not up yet'' (egō oupō anabainō — I am not yet going up). The key word is ''yet'' (oupō) — he will go, but not yet, and not publicly. ''My time is not yet full come'' (oupō peplērōtai — has not yet been fulfilled). Jesus is not being deceptive but deliberate: he will attend the feast on his own terms, in the Father''s timing, not as a public spectacle per his brothers'' plan.',
   NULL),
  (9, 'When he had said these words unto them, he abode still in Galilee.',
   'ταῦτα δὲ εἰπὼν αὐτοῖς ἔμεινεν ἐν τῇ Γαλιλαίᾳ',
   'tauta de eipōn autois emeinen en tē Galilaia',
   'Jesus remains in Galilee while his brothers depart. He waits — a pattern of divine restraint. The right action at the wrong time is the wrong action. Jesus waits for the Father''s moment, then acts decisively.',
   NULL),
  (10, 'But when his brethren were gone up, then went he also up unto the feast, not openly, but as it were in secret.',
   'ὡς δὲ ἀνέβησαν οἱ ἀδελφοὶ αὐτοῦ τότε καὶ αὐτὸς ἀνέβη εἰς τὴν ἑορτήν οὐ φανερῶς ἀλλ᾽ ὡς ἐν κρυπτῷ',
   'hōs de anebēsan hoi adelphoi autou tote kai autos anebē eis tēn heortēn ou phanerōs all hōs en kryptō',
   '''Not openly, but as it were in secret'' (ou phanerōs all hōs en kryptō — not publicly but as if in secret). Jesus goes to the feast privately, avoiding the public spectacle his brothers wanted. This is not stealth but strategic timing: he will teach publicly (v.14) but on his own schedule, not theirs. ''As it were'' (hōs) — he was not truly hiding but simply not making a public entrance.',
   NULL),
  (11, 'Then the Jews sought him at the feast, and said, Where is he?',
   'οἱ οὖν Ἰουδαῖοι ἐζήτουν αὐτὸν ἐν τῇ ἑορτῇ καὶ ἔλεγον Ποῦ ἐστιν ἐκεῖνος',
   'hoi oun Ioudaioi ezētoun auton en tē heortē kai elegon Pou estin ekeinos',
   '''The Jews'' (hoi Ioudaioi — the religious authorities, as John typically uses the term). ''Where is he?'' (pou estin ekeinos — where is that one?). The use of ''that one'' (ekeinos) without naming Jesus may express contempt or caution. Jesus has become the talk of the festival — his absence makes him more prominent, not less.',
   NULL),
  (12, 'And there was much murmuring among the people concerning him: for some said, He is a good man: others said, Nay; but he deceiveth the people.',
   'καὶ γογγυσμὸς πολὺς περὶ αὐτοῦ ἦν ἐν τοῖς ὄχλοις οἱ μὲν ἔλεγον ὅτι Ἀγαθός ἐστιν ἄλλοι δὲ ἔλεγον Οὔ ἀλλὰ πλανᾷ τὸν ὄχλον',
   'kai gongysmos polys peri autou ēn en tois ochlois hoi men elegon hoti Agathos estin alloi de elegon Ou alla plana ton ochlon',
   '''Much murmuring'' (gongysmos polys — much grumbling, whispering debate). The crowd is divided into two camps: ''He is a good man'' (agathos estin) vs. ''He deceiveth the people'' (plana ton ochlon — he leads the crowd astray). The charge of being a ''deceiver'' (planos) was later formalised in Jewish polemic against Jesus (cf. Matthew 27:63). There is no neutral position — Jesus forces a decision. C.S. Lewis''s famous trilemma echoes this: Jesus is either Lord, liar, or lunatic.',
   NULL),
  (13, 'Howbeit no man spake openly of him for fear of the Jews.',
   'οὐδεὶς μέντοι παρρησίᾳ ἐλάλει περὶ αὐτοῦ διὰ τὸν φόβον τῶν Ἰουδαίων',
   'oudeis mentoi parrēsia elalei peri autou dia ton phobon tōn Ioudaiōn',
   '''No man spake openly'' (oudeis parrēsia elalei — no one spoke with boldness/freedom). ''For fear of the Jews'' (dia ton phobon tōn Ioudaiōn — because of the fear of the Jewish authorities). The religious leaders had created an atmosphere of intimidation. People whispered about Jesus but dared not speak publicly. This fear will intensify (cf. 9:22; 12:42; 19:38; 20:19). Fear of man silences truth — a recurring biblical theme (Proverbs 29:25).',
   NULL),
  (14, 'Now about the midst of the feast Jesus went up into the temple, and taught.',
   'ἤδη δὲ τῆς ἑορτῆς μεσούσης ἀνέβη ὁ Ἰησοῦς εἰς τὸ ἱερόν καὶ ἐδίδασκεν',
   'ēdē de tēs heortēs mesousēs anebē ho Iēsous eis to hieron kai edidasken',
   '''About the midst of the feast'' (tēs heortēs mesousēs — the feast being at its midpoint, around day 3 or 4 of the 7-day festival). Jesus now appears publicly — not at the beginning (when everyone expected) but in the middle (when he chooses). He teaches in the temple (to hieron — the temple complex, likely in one of the porticoes or courts). His teaching provokes the astonishment of v.15.',
   NULL),
  (15, 'And the Jews marvelled, saying, How knoweth this man letters, having never learned?',
   'ἐθαύμαζον οὖν οἱ Ἰουδαῖοι λέγοντες Πῶς οὗτος γράμματα οἶδεν μὴ μεμαθηκώς',
   'ethaumazon oun hoi Ioudaioi legontes Pōs houtos grammata oiden mē memathēkōs',
   '''How knoweth this man letters?'' (pōs houtos grammata oiden — how does this one know writings/learning?). ''Having never learned'' (mē memathēkōs — not having been a student; he never studied under a recognised rabbi). Jesus had no formal rabbinic education — he was not a disciple of Gamaliel, Hillel, or Shammai. Yet his scriptural knowledge and teaching ability surpassed the trained scholars. The source of his learning is explained in v.16.',
   NULL),
  (16, 'Jesus answered them, and said, My doctrine is not mine, but his that sent me.',
   'ἀπεκρίθη οὖν αὐτοῖς ὁ Ἰησοῦς καὶ εἶπεν Ἡ ἐμὴ διδαχὴ οὐκ ἔστιν ἐμὴ ἀλλὰ τοῦ πέμψαντός με',
   'apekrithē oun autois ho Iēsous kai eipen Hē emē didachē ouk estin emē alla tou pempsantos me',
   '''My doctrine is not mine'' (hē emē didachē ouk estin emē — my teaching is not my own). ''But his that sent me'' (alla tou pempsantos me — but belongs to the one who sent me). Jesus'' teaching comes directly from the Father — not from rabbinic training. This is both a claim to divine authority (his teaching is God''s teaching) and a model of humility (he does not speak independently). The pattern is consistent with 5:19: ''The Son can do nothing of himself.''',
   NULL),
  (17, 'If any man will do his will, he shall know of the doctrine, whether it be of God, or whether I speak of myself.',
   'ἐάν τις θέλῃ τὸ θέλημα αὐτοῦ ποιεῖν γνώσεται περὶ τῆς διδαχῆς πότερον ἐκ τοῦ θεοῦ ἐστιν ἢ ἐγὼ ἀπ᾽ ἐμαυτοῦ λαλῶ',
   'ean tis thelē to thelēma autou poiein gnōsetai peri tēs didachēs poteron ek tou theou estin ē egō ap emautou lalō',
   '''If any man will do his will'' (ean tis thelē to thelēma autou poiein — if anyone desires/wills to do God''s will). ''He shall know of the doctrine'' (gnōsetai peri tēs didachēs — he will come to know about the teaching). The test of divine doctrine is not intellectual analysis but moral obedience. The person who sincerely desires to do God''s will receives spiritual discernment to recognise God''s truth. Unbelief is not primarily an intellectual problem but a moral one — those who resist God''s will cannot perceive God''s truth.',
   NULL),
  (18, 'He that speaketh of himself seeketh his own glory: but he that seeketh his glory that sent him, the same is true, and no unrighteousness is in him.',
   'ὁ ἀφ᾽ ἑαυτοῦ λαλῶν τὴν δόξαν τὴν ἰδίαν ζητεῖ ὁ δὲ ζητῶν τὴν δόξαν τοῦ πέμψαντος αὐτόν οὗτος ἀληθής ἐστιν καὶ ἀδικία ἐν αὐτῷ οὐκ ἔστιν',
   'ho aph heautou lalōn tēn doxan tēn idian zētei ho de zētōn tēn doxan tou pempsantos auton houtos alēthēs estin kai adikia en autō ouk estin',
   'A principle for evaluating teachers: self-promoters seek their own glory (tēn doxan tēn idian) and are unreliable. The one who seeks the glory of God who sent him is true (alēthēs) and without unrighteousness (adikia ouk estin). Jesus applies this to himself: since he seeks the Father''s glory, not his own, his testimony is trustworthy. This criterion also applies to all ministers of the gospel — the test of authenticity is whether they seek God''s glory or their own.',
   NULL),
  (19, 'Did not Moses give you the law, and yet none of you keepeth the law? Why go ye about to kill me?',
   'οὐ Μωϋσῆς δέδωκεν ὑμῖν τὸν νόμον καὶ οὐδεὶς ἐξ ὑμῶν ποιεῖ τὸν νόμον τί με ζητεῖτε ἀποκτεῖναι',
   'ou Mōysēs dedōken hymin ton nomon kai oudeis ex hymōn poiei ton nomon ti me zēteite apokteinai',
   'Jesus turns the tables: they accuse him of breaking the Sabbath law, but none of them keeps the entire law. ''Why go ye about to kill me?'' (ti me zēteite apokteinai — why are you seeking to kill me?). Murder is a far greater violation of the law than Sabbath healing. Their zeal for law-keeping is selective and hypocritical — they enforce minor points while planning to violate the sixth commandment.',
   NULL),
  (20, 'The people answered and said, Thou hast a devil: who goeth about to kill thee?',
   'ἀπεκρίθη ὁ ὄχλος καὶ εἶπεν Δαιμόνιον ἔχεις τίς σε ζητεῖ ἀποκτεῖναι',
   'apekrithē ho ochlos kai eipen Daimonion echeis tis se zētei apokteinai',
   '''Thou hast a devil'' (daimonion echeis — you have a demon; meaning: you are mad, deranged). The crowd (ochlos, not the Jewish leaders) is unaware of the plot against Jesus'' life. Their denial (''Who goeth about to kill thee?'') is innocent but ironic — the leaders are indeed planning murder (5:18; 7:1, 25). The charge of demon-possession will recur (8:48, 52; 10:20).',
   NULL),
  (21, 'Jesus answered and said unto them, I have done one work, and ye all marvel.',
   'ἀπεκρίθη Ἰησοῦς καὶ εἶπεν αὐτοῖς Ἓν ἔργον ἐποίησα καὶ πάντες θαυμάζετε',
   'apekrithē Iēsous kai eipen autois Hen ergon epoiēsa kai pantes thaumazete',
   '''One work'' (hen ergon — one deed). This refers back to the healing at Bethesda (5:1-16) — the single act that triggered the murder plot. Despite the many miracles Jesus has performed, this one work on the Sabbath has consumed them. They marvel (thaumazete — are amazed, disturbed) at it still, months later.',
   NULL),
  (22, 'Moses therefore gave unto you circumcision; (not because it is of Moses, but of the fathers;) and ye on the sabbath day circumcise a man.',
   'διὰ τοῦτο Μωϋσῆς δέδωκεν ὑμῖν τὴν περιτομήν οὐχ ὅτι ἐκ τοῦ Μωϋσέως ἐστὶν ἀλλ᾽ ἐκ τῶν πατέρων καὶ ἐν σαββάτῳ περιτέμνετε ἄνθρωπον',
   'dia touto Mōysēs dedōken hymin tēn peritomēn ouch hoti ek tou Mōyseōs estin all ek tōn paterōn kai en sabbatō peritemnete anthrōpon',
   'Jesus uses a rabbinic argument from the lesser to the greater (qal wahomer). Circumcision originated with the patriarchs (Abraham, Genesis 17:10-12) and was incorporated into the Mosaic law (Leviticus 12:3). When the eighth day falls on the Sabbath, circumcision is still performed — the Jews themselves override the Sabbath rest for one part of one body. The argument is irrefutable within their own legal framework.',
   NULL),
  (23, 'If a man on the sabbath day receive circumcision, that the law of Moses should not be broken; are ye angry at me, because I have made a man every whit whole on the sabbath day?',
   'εἰ περιτομὴν λαμβάνει ἄνθρωπος ἐν σαββάτῳ ἵνα μὴ λυθῇ ὁ νόμος Μωϋσέως ἐμοὶ χολᾶτε ὅτι ὅλον ἄνθρωπον ὑγιῆ ἐποίησα ἐν σαββάτῳ',
   'ei peritomēn lambanei anthrōpos en sabbatō hina mē lythē ho nomos Mōyseōs emoi cholate hoti holon anthrōpon hygiē epoiēsa en sabbatō',
   '''Every whit whole'' (holon anthrōpon hygiē — a whole man well; the entire person made healthy). The argument: if you circumcise one member on the Sabbath to keep the law, why are you angry that I made an entire man whole? Circumcision perfects one part; healing perfects the whole. If the lesser act is permitted, the greater act should certainly be permitted. ''Are ye angry at me?'' (emoi cholate — are you bitter toward me? From cholaō: to be full of bile, to be furious).',
   NULL),
  (24, 'Judge not according to the appearance, but judge righteous judgment.',
   'μὴ κρίνετε κατ᾽ ὄψιν ἀλλὰ τὴν δικαίαν κρίσιν κρίνατε',
   'mē krinete kat opsin alla tēn dikaian krisin krinate',
   '''Judge not according to the appearance'' (mē krinete kat opsin — do not judge by surface, by what meets the eye). ''Judge righteous judgment'' (tēn dikaian krisin krinate — judge with just/fair judgment). Jesus does not prohibit all judging but demands righteous judging. They judged superficially: a man carried his bed on the Sabbath — guilty! But righteous judgment considers the whole picture: a man was healed after 38 years of suffering. Appearance says ''Sabbath violation''; righteousness says ''God is at work.''',
   NULL),
  (25, 'Then said some of them of Jerusalem, Is not this he whom they seek to kill?',
   'ἔλεγον οὖν τινες ἐκ τῶν Ἱεροσολυμιτῶν Οὐχ οὗτός ἐστιν ὃν ζητοῦσιν ἀποκτεῖναι',
   'elegon oun tines ek tōn Hierosolymitōn Ouch houtos estin hon zētousin apokteinai',
   'The Jerusalem residents (Hierosolymitōn — distinguished from the pilgrim crowds in v.20) know about the murder plot. Their question implies: this is indeed the man the authorities want to kill. Their awareness vindicates Jesus'' statement in v.19.',
   NULL),
  (26, 'But, lo, he speaketh boldly, and they say nothing unto him. Do the rulers know indeed that this is the very Christ?',
   'καὶ ἴδε παρρησίᾳ λαλεῖ καὶ οὐδὲν αὐτῷ λέγουσιν μήποτε ἀληθῶς ἔγνωσαν οἱ ἄρχοντες ὅτι οὗτός ἐστιν ἀληθῶς ὁ Χριστός',
   'kai ide parrēsia lalei kai ouden autō legousin mēpote alēthōs egnōsan hoi archontes hoti houtos estin alēthōs ho Christos',
   '''He speaketh boldly'' (parrēsia lalei — with freedom, openly, without restraint). The crowd reasons: if the authorities want him dead, why do they let him speak publicly? Perhaps they have secretly concluded he is the Christ? The question reveals growing messianic expectation — the people are open to the possibility, even if the leaders are not.',
   NULL),
  (27, 'Howbeit we know this man whence he is: but when Christ cometh, no man knoweth whence he is.',
   'ἀλλὰ τοῦτον οἴδαμεν πόθεν ἐστίν ὁ δὲ Χριστὸς ὅταν ἔρχηται οὐδεὶς γινώσκει πόθεν ἐστίν',
   'alla touton oidamen pothen estin ho de Christos hotan erchētai oudeis ginōskei pothen estin',
   '''We know this man whence he is'' — they know Jesus is from Nazareth in Galilee. ''When Christ cometh, no man knoweth whence he is'' — a popular Jewish belief that the Messiah would appear suddenly, mysteriously (cf. Malachi 3:1; the ''hidden Messiah'' tradition). Their reasoning: we know where Jesus comes from, therefore he cannot be the Messiah. The irony is devastating: they think they know his origin (Nazareth) but they do not know his true origin (heaven, from the Father).',
   NULL),
  (28, 'Then cried Jesus in the temple as he taught, saying, Ye both know me, and ye know whence I am: and I am not come of myself, but he that sent me is true, whom ye know not.',
   'ἔκραξεν οὖν ἐν τῷ ἱερῷ διδάσκων ὁ Ἰησοῦς καὶ λέγων Κἀμὲ οἴδατε καὶ οἴδατε πόθεν εἰμί καὶ ἀπ᾽ ἐμαυτοῦ οὐκ ἐλήλυθα ἀλλ᾽ ἔστιν ἀληθινὸς ὁ πέμψας με ὃν ὑμεῖς οὐκ οἴδατε',
   'ekraxen oun en tō hierō didaskōn ho Iēsous kai legōn Kame oidate kai oidate pothen eimi kai ap emautou ouk elēlytha all estin alēthinos ho pempsas me hon hymeis ouk oidate',
   '''Cried'' (ekraxen — shouted, cried out; a loud, public declaration). ''Ye both know me, and ye know whence I am'' — this may be ironic (you think you know but you do not), or concessive (yes, you know my earthly origin, but there is more). ''I am not come of myself'' (ap emautou ouk elēlytha — I have not come on my own initiative). ''He that sent me is true'' (estin alēthinos ho pempsas me — the one who sent me is genuine, real). ''Whom ye know not'' (hon hymeis ouk oidate — whom you do not know). The devastating charge: they claim to know God but do not know the one who sent Jesus.',
   NULL),
  (29, 'But I know him: for I am from him, and he hath sent me.',
   'ἐγὼ δὲ οἶδα αὐτόν ὅτι παρ᾽ αὐτοῦ εἰμι κἀκεῖνός με ἀπέστειλεν',
   'egō de oida auton hoti par autou eimi kakeinos me apesteilen',
   '''I know him'' (egō oida auton — I, I know him; emphatic pronoun). ''I am from him'' (par autou eimi — I am from his presence, from his side). ''He hath sent me'' (kakeinos me apesteilen — and that one sent me). Two claims: (1) Jesus originates from the Father — pre-existence. (2) The Father has commissioned/sent him — divine mission. Together they assert unique intimacy with and authority from God.',
   NULL),
  (30, 'Then they sought to take him: but no man laid hands on him, because his hour was not yet come.',
   'ἐζήτουν οὖν αὐτὸν πιάσαι καὶ οὐδεὶς ἐπέβαλεν ἐπ᾽ αὐτὸν τὴν χεῖρα ὅτι οὔπω ἐληλύθει ἡ ὥρα αὐτοῦ',
   'ezētoun oun auton piasai kai oudeis epebalen ep auton tēn cheira hoti oupō elēlythei hē hōra autou',
   '''No man laid hands on him'' (oudeis epebalen tēn cheira — no one put a hand on him). ''His hour was not yet come'' (oupō elēlythei hē hōra autou — his hour had not yet arrived). John''s ''hour'' (hōra) refers to the appointed time of Jesus'' death and glorification (cf. 2:4; 7:30; 8:20; 12:23, 27; 13:1; 17:1). No human scheme can accelerate or prevent God''s timetable. Jesus is untouchable until the Father''s hour arrives.',
   NULL),
  (31, 'And many of the people believed on him, and said, When Christ cometh, will he do more miracles than these which this man hath done?',
   'πολλοὶ δὲ ἐκ τοῦ ὄχλου ἐπίστευσαν εἰς αὐτὸν καὶ ἔλεγον Ὁ Χριστὸς ὅταν ἔλθῃ μήτι πλείονα σημεῖα τούτων ποιήσει ὧν οὗτος ἐποίησεν',
   'polloi de ek tou ochlou episteusan eis auton kai elegon Ho Christos hotan elthē mēti pleiona sēmeia toutōn poiēsei hōn houtos epoiēsen',
   '''Many of the people believed'' (polloi episteusan — many believed). Their reasoning: even when the Messiah comes, can he surpass Jesus'' signs? The implied answer is no — therefore Jesus must be the Messiah. This is sign-based faith, better than rejection but not yet mature faith (cf. 2:23-25). The question with mēti expects a negative answer: ''Surely the Christ won''t do more signs than this man?''',
   NULL),
  (32, 'The Pharisees heard that the people murmured such things concerning him; and the Pharisees and the chief priests sent officers to take him.',
   'ἤκουσαν οἱ Φαρισαῖοι τοῦ ὄχλου γογγύζοντος περὶ αὐτοῦ ταῦτα καὶ ἀπέστειλαν οἱ Φαρισαῖοι καὶ οἱ ἀρχιερεῖς ὑπηρέτας ἵνα πιάσωσιν αὐτόν',
   'ēkousan hoi Pharisaioi tou ochlou gongyzontos peri autou tauta kai apesteilan hoi Pharisaioi kai hoi archiereis hypēretas hina piasōsin auton',
   '''The Pharisees and the chief priests'' — a rare joint action between Pharisees and Sadducean chief priests who normally disagreed. Opposition to Jesus unites theological enemies (cf. Luke 23:12: Herod and Pilate became friends). ''Sent officers'' (apesteilan hypēretas — dispatched temple police/attendants; hypēretēs: an under-rower, a subordinate servant). The officers are sent to arrest Jesus but will return empty-handed (v.45-46).',
   NULL),
  (33, 'Then said Jesus unto them, Yet a little while am I with you, and then I go unto him that sent me.',
   'εἶπεν οὖν ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ἔτι μικρὸν χρόνον μεθ᾽ ὑμῶν εἰμι καὶ ὑπάγω πρὸς τὸν πέμψαντά με',
   'eipen oun ho Iēsous Eti mikron chronon meth hymōn eimi kai hypagō pros ton pempsanta me',
   '''Yet a little while'' (eti mikron chronon — still a small time). ''I go unto him that sent me'' — referring to his death, resurrection, and ascension (the ''going to the Father,'' cf. 13:1; 14:28; 16:5, 28). Jesus speaks of his death not as defeat but as departure — a going home to the Father. The brevity of his remaining time adds urgency.',
   NULL),
  (34, 'Ye shall seek me, and shall not find me: and where I am, thither ye cannot come.',
   'ζητήσετέ με καὶ οὐχ εὑρήσετέ με καὶ ὅπου εἰμὶ ἐγὼ ὑμεῖς οὐ δύνασθε ἐλθεῖν',
   'zētēsete me kai ouch heurēsete me kai hopou eimi egō hymeis ou dynasthe elthein',
   '''Ye shall seek me, and shall not find me'' — this is a warning, not a promise. After Jesus departs, those who rejected him will seek him in vain. ''Where I am, thither ye cannot come'' (hopou eimi egō hymeis ou dynasthe elthein — where I am you cannot come). Jesus is going to the Father; unbelievers cannot follow. The saying is enigmatic to the audience (v.35-36) but clear to John''s readers: Jesus speaks of his exaltation to the Father''s right hand.',
   NULL),
  (35, 'Then said the Jews among themselves, Whither will he go, that we shall not find him? will he go unto the dispersed among the Gentiles, and teach the Gentiles?',
   'εἶπον οὖν οἱ Ἰουδαῖοι πρὸς ἑαυτούς Ποῦ οὗτος μέλλει πορεύεσθαι ὅτι ἡμεῖς οὐχ εὑρήσομεν αὐτόν μὴ εἰς τὴν διασπορὰν τῶν Ἑλλήνων μέλλει πορεύεσθαι καὶ διδάσκειν τοὺς Ἕλληνας',
   'eipon oun hoi Ioudaioi pros heautous Pou houtos mellei poreuesthai hoti hēmeis ouch heurēsomen auton mē eis tēn diasporan tōn Hellēnōn mellei poreuesthai kai didaskein tous Hellēnas',
   '''The dispersed among the Gentiles'' (tēn diasporan tōn Hellēnōn — the Diaspora among the Greeks; Jewish communities scattered throughout the Greco-Roman world). They wonder if Jesus will leave Palestine to teach among Diaspora Jews and Greeks. The suggestion is dismissive but ironically prophetic: through his apostles and the church, Jesus'' teaching will indeed reach the Gentile world (cf. 12:20-23 where Greeks come seeking Jesus).',
   NULL),
  (36, 'What manner of saying is this that he said, Ye shall seek me, and shall not find me: and where I am, thither ye cannot come?',
   'τίς ἐστιν οὗτος ὁ λόγος ὃν εἶπεν Ζητήσετέ με καὶ οὐχ εὑρήσετέ με καὶ ὅπου εἰμὶ ἐγὼ ὑμεῖς οὐ δύνασθε ἐλθεῖν',
   'tis estin houtos ho logos hon eipen Zētēsete me kai ouch heurēsete me kai hopou eimi egō hymeis ou dynasthe elthein',
   'They are baffled by Jesus'' enigmatic saying. Their confusion is part of John''s pattern: Jesus speaks on a heavenly plane; his listeners interpret on an earthly plane. The saying will be repeated in 8:21 with greater urgency: ''Ye shall seek me, and shall die in your sins.''',
   NULL),
  (37, 'In the last day, that great day of the feast, Jesus stood and cried, saying, If any man thirst, let him come unto me, and drink.',
   'ἐν δὲ τῇ ἐσχάτῃ ἡμέρᾳ τῇ μεγάλῃ τῆς ἑορτῆς εἱστήκει ὁ Ἰησοῦς καὶ ἔκραξεν λέγων Ἐάν τις διψᾷ ἐρχέσθω πρός με καὶ πινέτω',
   'en de tē eschatē hēmera tē megalē tēs heortēs heistēkei ho Iēsous kai ekraxen legōn Ean tis dipsa erchesthō pros me kai pinetō',
   '''The last day, that great day'' (tē eschatē hēmera tē megalē — the last day, the great one). This is either the seventh day (the climax of the water-pouring ceremony) or the eighth day (the solemn assembly, Leviticus 23:36). During Tabernacles, a priest drew water from the Pool of Siloam in a golden pitcher and poured it on the altar while the people sang Isaiah 12:3: ''With joy shall ye draw water out of the wells of salvation.'' At this precise moment, Jesus stands (heistēkei — stood up, rose to his feet; a dramatic gesture) and cries out with a loud voice: ''If any man thirst, let him come unto me, and drink.'' He claims to be the fulfilment of everything the water ceremony symbolised.',
   'This is one of the great christological claims of the Gospel. The Feast of Tabernacles commemorated God''s provision of water from the rock in the wilderness (Exodus 17:6; Numbers 20:11). The water-pouring ceremony expressed Israel''s dependence on God for rain and life. Into this liturgical moment, Jesus inserts himself as the ultimate source: not the rock, not the ceremony, not the pool — but ''come unto me, and drink.'' Paul identifies the rock as Christ (1 Corinthians 10:4). Isaiah promised rivers in the desert (Isaiah 35:6-7; 43:19-20; 44:3). Jesus claims to fulfil all these promises in his own person. The invitation is universal (''any man''), the condition is need (''thirst''), and the response is personal (''come unto me'').'),
  (38, 'He that believeth on me, as the scripture hath said, out of his belly shall flow rivers of living water.',
   'ὁ πιστεύων εἰς ἐμέ καθὼς εἶπεν ἡ γραφή ποταμοὶ ἐκ τῆς κοιλίας αὐτοῦ ῥεύσουσιν ὕδατος ζῶντος',
   'ho pisteuōn eis eme kathōs eipen hē graphē potamoi ek tēs koilias autou rheusousin hydatos zōntos',
   '''Rivers of living water'' (potamoi hydatos zōntos — rivers of water that is alive, flowing, fresh). ''Out of his belly'' (ek tēs koilias autou — from his innermost being). The ''scripture'' Jesus cites may be Isaiah 58:11, Ezekiel 47:1-12, Zechariah 14:8, or a combination. The promise is extraordinary: the believer not only receives living water but becomes a source — rivers flowing outward to others. The one who drinks from Christ overflows to bless the world.',
   NULL),
  (39, '(But this spake he of the Spirit, which they that believe on him should receive: for the Holy Ghost was not yet given; because that Jesus was not yet glorified.)',
   'τοῦτο δὲ εἶπεν περὶ τοῦ πνεύματος οὗ ἔμελλον λαμβάνειν οἱ πιστεύοντες εἰς αὐτόν οὔπω γὰρ ἦν πνεῦμα ἅγιον ὅτι Ἰησοῦς οὐδέπω ἐδοξάσθη',
   'touto de eipen peri tou pneumatos hou emellon lambanein hoi pisteuontes eis auton oupō gar ēn pneuma hagion hoti Iēsous oudepō edoxasthē',
   'John''s editorial comment provides the definitive interpretation: the ''living water'' is the Holy Spirit. ''The Holy Ghost was not yet given'' (oupō ēn pneuma hagion — the Spirit was not yet, meaning not yet poured out in fullness). The Spirit existed and was active in the OT, but the fullness of the Spirit''s indwelling ministry awaited Jesus'' glorification (his death, resurrection, and ascension). Pentecost (Acts 2) fulfils this promise. The sequence is: cross → resurrection → ascension → Spirit''s outpouring.',
   'The connection between Jesus'' glorification and the Spirit''s coming is fundamental to NT theology. The Spirit could not be given in fullness until Jesus completed his atoning work: ''It is expedient for you that I go away: for if I go not away, the Comforter will not come unto you; but if I depart, I will send him unto you'' (John 16:7). The Spirit''s ministry is to apply the benefits of Christ''s finished work to believers. The ''rivers of living water'' are the Spirit producing the fruit of the Spirit (Galatians 5:22-23) and empowering witness (Acts 1:8) in and through believers.'),
  (40, 'Many of the people therefore, when they heard this saying, said, Of a truth this is the Prophet.',
   'πολλοὶ οὖν ἐκ τοῦ ὄχλου ἀκούσαντες τὸν λόγον ἔλεγον Οὗτός ἐστιν ἀληθῶς ὁ προφήτης',
   'polloi oun ek tou ochlou akousantes ton logon elegon Houtos estin alēthōs ho prophētēs',
   '''The Prophet'' (ho prophētēs — the definite article: the Prophet, the specific one foretold by Moses in Deuteronomy 18:15). Some identify Jesus as this Prophet — a correct identification, but incomplete if it excludes his identity as the Christ. In first-century Judaism, ''the Prophet'' and ''the Christ'' were sometimes distinguished as separate figures (cf. 1:20-21).',
   NULL),
  (41, 'Others said, This is the Christ. But some said, Shall Christ come out of Galilee?',
   'ἄλλοι ἔλεγον Οὗτός ἐστιν ὁ Χριστός ἄλλοι δὲ ἔλεγον Μὴ γὰρ ἐκ τῆς Γαλιλαίας ὁ Χριστὸς ἔρχεται',
   'alloi elegon Houtos estin ho Christos alloi de elegon Mē gar ek tēs Galilaias ho Christos erchetai',
   '''This is the Christ'' — others go further, identifying Jesus as the Messiah. But objectors ask: ''Shall Christ come out of Galilee?'' The question assumes a negative answer: the Messiah cannot be Galilean. The irony is layered: (1) Jesus was born in Bethlehem (Matthew 2:1; Luke 2:4-7), fulfilling the Micah 5:2 prophecy. (2) The crowd does not know this — their objection is based on incomplete information. (3) John does not correct them directly, trusting his readers to see the irony.',
   NULL),
  (42, 'Hath not the scripture said, That Christ cometh of the seed of David, and out of the town of Bethlehem, where David was?',
   'οὐχὶ ἡ γραφὴ εἶπεν ὅτι ἐκ τοῦ σπέρματος Δαυὶδ καὶ ἀπὸ Βηθλέεμ τῆς κώμης ὅπου ἦν Δαυὶδ ὁ Χριστὸς ἔρχεται',
   'ouchi hē graphē eipen hoti ek tou spermatos Dauid kai apo Bēthleem tēs kōmēs hopou ēn Dauid ho Christos erchetai',
   'The crowd correctly cites Scripture: the Messiah comes from David''s line (2 Samuel 7:12; Isaiah 11:1) and from Bethlehem (Micah 5:2). Their theology is correct; their application is wrong. They assume Jesus does not meet these criteria because they know him only as ''Jesus of Nazareth.'' John''s irony is profound: the very Scriptures they cite to dismiss Jesus actually confirm him — he is of David''s line and was born in Bethlehem.',
   NULL),
  (43, 'So there was a division among the people because of him.',
   'σχίσμα οὖν ἐν τῷ ὄχλῳ ἐγένετο δι᾽ αὐτόν',
   'schisma oun en tō ochlō egeneto di auton',
   '''Division'' (schisma — a split, tear, division; from schizō: to tear, split). Jesus causes division wherever he goes (cf. 9:16; 10:19; Matthew 10:34-36: ''I came not to send peace, but a sword''). This is not a failure of his ministry but its inevitable result: light divides from darkness, truth divides from error. Neutrality toward Christ is impossible.',
   NULL),
  (44, 'And some of them would have taken him; but no man laid hands on him.',
   'τινὲς δὲ ἤθελον ἐξ αὐτῶν πιάσαι αὐτόν ἀλλ᾽ οὐδεὶς ἐπέβαλεν ἐπ᾽ αὐτὸν τὰς χεῖρας',
   'tines de ēthelon ex autōn piasai auton all oudeis epebalen ep auton tas cheiras',
   'Again, the attempt to seize Jesus fails (cf. v.30). Human hands cannot touch him until the Father''s appointed hour (cf. 10:39; 18:4-6). Jesus is sovereign even over his own arrest — he cannot be taken, only given (10:17-18).',
   NULL),
  (45, 'Then came the officers to the chief priests and Pharisees; and they said unto them, Why have ye not brought him?',
   'ἦλθον οὖν οἱ ὑπηρέται πρὸς τοὺς ἀρχιερεῖς καὶ Φαρισαίους καὶ εἶπον αὐτοῖς ἐκεῖνοι Διατί οὐκ ἠγάγετε αὐτόν',
   'ēlthon oun hoi hypēretai pros tous archiereis kai Pharisaious kai eipon autois ekeinoi Diati ouk ēgagete auton',
   'The temple officers return to the Sanhedrin without Jesus. ''Why have ye not brought him?'' (diati ouk ēgagete auton — why did you not bring him?). They were sent to arrest him (v.32) but failed — or rather, refused. Their explanation in v.46 is remarkable.',
   NULL),
  (46, 'The officers answered, Never man spake like this man.',
   'ἀπεκρίθησαν οἱ ὑπηρέται Οὐδέποτε οὕτως ἐλάλησεν ἄνθρωπος ὡς οὗτος ὁ ἄνθρωπος',
   'apekrithēsan hoi hypēretai Oudepote houtōs elalēsen anthrōpos hōs houtos ho anthrōpos',
   '''Never man spake like this man'' (oudepote houtōs elalēsen anthrōpos — never has a man spoken like this). The temple police — trained, professional, accustomed to religious discourse — were so overcome by Jesus'' teaching that they could not arrest him. They do not say ''He escaped'' or ''We could not find him'' — they confess they were disarmed by his words. This is an involuntary testimony from hostile witnesses: Jesus'' speech is without parallel in human history.',
   NULL),
  (47, 'Then answered them the Pharisees, Are ye also deceived?',
   'ἀπεκρίθησαν οὖν αὐτοῖς οἱ Φαρισαῖοι Μὴ καὶ ὑμεῖς πεπλάνησθε',
   'apekrithēsan oun autois hoi Pharisaioi Mē kai hymeis peplanēsthe',
   '''Are ye also deceived?'' (mē kai hymeis peplanēsthe — surely you also have not been led astray? Perfect passive: have you been deceived and remain so?). The Pharisees respond with contempt and social pressure: you too? Even you, our own officers? Their argument is not exegetical but sociological: the right people don''t believe in Jesus.',
   NULL),
  (48, 'Have any of the rulers or of the Pharisees believed on him?',
   'μή τις ἐκ τῶν ἀρχόντων ἐπίστευσεν εἰς αὐτὸν ἢ ἐκ τῶν Φαρισαίων',
   'mē tis ek tōn archontōn episteusen eis auton ē ek tōn Pharisaiōn',
   '''Have any of the rulers or Pharisees believed?'' The implied answer is ''no'' — and the conclusion is: therefore he is not the Messiah. Their criterion for truth is peer approval, not evidence. This is the exact error Jesus identified in 5:44: ''How can ye believe, which receive honour one of another?'' The irony: at least one ruler has come to Jesus — Nicodemus, standing right there (v.50). And later, Joseph of Arimathea will confess faith (19:38).',
   NULL),
  (49, 'But this people who knoweth not the law are cursed.',
   'ἀλλ᾽ ὁ ὄχλος οὗτος ὁ μὴ γινώσκων τὸν νόμον ἐπικατάρατοί εἰσιν',
   'all ho ochlos houtos ho mē ginōskōn ton nomon epikatáratoi eisin',
   '''This people who knoweth not the law are cursed'' — the Pharisees dismiss the common people as ''am ha-aretz'' (people of the land) — ignorant, unlearned in Torah, and therefore cursed. This is religious elitism at its worst: the unlearned cannot discern truth, so their opinions are worthless. The irony is that the ''unlearned'' people correctly discern Jesus while the ''learned'' Pharisees reject him. God reveals truth to ''babes'' and hides it from the ''wise'' (Matthew 11:25).',
   NULL),
  (50, 'Nicodemus saith unto them, (he that came to Jesus by night, being one of them,)',
   'λέγει Νικόδημος πρὸς αὐτούς ὁ ἐλθὼν νυκτὸς πρὸς αὐτὸν εἷς ὢν ἐξ αὐτῶν',
   'legei Nikodēmos pros autous ho elthōn nyktos pros auton heis ōn ex autōn',
   'Nicodemus reappears — ''he that came to Jesus by night'' (ho elthōn nyktos, cf. 3:1-2), ''being one of them'' (heis ōn ex autōn — one of the Pharisees/Sanhedrin). He does not openly defend Jesus but raises a procedural objection — a cautious step. His faith is growing but still timid (he will appear again at the burial, 19:39, openly identifying with Jesus). Nicodemus represents the journey from secret belief to public confession.',
   NULL),
  (51, 'Doth our law judge any man, before it hear him, and know what he doeth?',
   'Μὴ ὁ νόμος ἡμῶν κρίνει τὸν ἄνθρωπον ἐὰν μὴ ἀκούσῃ παρ᾽ αὐτοῦ πρότερον καὶ γνῷ τί ποιεῖ',
   'Mē ho nomos hēmōn krinei ton anthrōpon ean mē akousē par autou proteron kai gnō ti poiei',
   '''Doth our law judge any man before it hear him?'' — Nicodemus appeals to legal procedure: Deuteronomy 1:16-17 and 17:2-6 require hearing a case before rendering judgment. The Pharisees are condemning Jesus without a proper trial. Nicodemus does not declare faith but insists on fairness — a principled defence that exposes their hypocrisy. They are violating the very law they claim Jesus is breaking.',
   NULL),
  (52, 'They answered and said unto him, Art thou also of Galilee? Search, and look: for out of Galilee ariseth no prophet.',
   'ἀπεκρίθησαν καὶ εἶπον αὐτῷ Μὴ καὶ σὺ ἐκ τῆς Γαλιλαίας εἶ ἐρεύνησον καὶ ἴδε ὅτι προφήτης ἐκ τῆς Γαλιλαίας οὐκ ἐγήγερται',
   'apekrithēsan kai eipon autō Mē kai sy ek tēs Galilaias ei ereunēson kai ide hoti prophētēs ek tēs Galilaias ouk egēgertai',
   '''Art thou also of Galilee?'' — a sneer: are you too a Galilean sympathiser? ''Search, and look: for out of Galilee ariseth no prophet'' — this is factually incorrect. Jonah was from Gath-hepher in Galilee (2 Kings 14:25). Nahum was possibly from Galilee (Elkosh). Elijah may have been from Galilee. The Pharisees'' dismissive certainty is based on prejudice, not scholarship. They tell Nicodemus to ''search'' (ereunēson) the Scriptures — the same verb Jesus used in 5:39.',
   NULL),
  (53, 'And every man went unto his own house.',
   'καὶ ἐπορεύθη ἕκαστος εἰς τὸν οἶκον αὐτοῦ',
   'kai eporeuthē hekastos eis ton oikon autou',
   '''Every man went unto his own house'' — the meeting breaks up inconclusively. No arrest, no resolution, no consensus. The chapter ends as it began: with division. Everyone goes home, but the question of Jesus'' identity remains unanswered — for them. John''s readers know the answer. Note: 7:53-8:11 (the woman caught in adultery) is absent from the earliest manuscripts and is likely a later insertion, though the story itself may be historically authentic.',
   NULL)
) AS v(verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
WHERE b.name = 'John' AND c.chapter_number = 7;

-- Step 3: Insert word studies
INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, greek_word, transliteration, strongs_number, definition, word_order)
SELECT v.id, ws.greek_word, ws.transliteration, ws.strongs_number, ws.definition, ws.word_order
FROM verses v
JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  ('σκηνοπηγία', 'skēnopēgia', 'G4634',
   'The Feast of Tabernacles, the feast of tent-pitching, the feast of booths.',
   'From skēnē (tent, tabernacle) + pēgnymi (to pitch, fix firmly). The feast (Leviticus 23:33-43) commemorated Israel''s wilderness wandering when they lived in tents. For seven days, Jews built and lived in temporary booths (sukkot) as a reminder of their dependence on God. The feast also celebrated the autumn harvest (''the feast of ingathering,'' Exodus 23:16). Key ceremonies included water-pouring and light-illumination — both of which Jesus claims to fulfil (7:37-38; 8:12). Zechariah 14:16-19 prophesied that in the messianic age, all nations would celebrate Tabernacles.',
   1),
  ('καιρός', 'kairos', 'G2540',
   'Time, season, appointed time, opportune moment; the right or favourable time for action.',
   'In v.6, Jesus says ''My kairos is not yet come'' (ho kairos ho emos oupō parestin). Kairos differs from chronos (time in general) in denoting a specific, significant moment — the divinely appointed season. Jesus'' kairos is his hour of glorification through the cross (cf. hōra in v.30). The brothers'' kairos ''is alway ready'' because they have no divine appointment. Every moment of Jesus'' ministry is calibrated to the Father''s timetable. Kairos in the NT often refers to the decisive moment of God''s action (Mark 1:15: ''the kairos is fulfilled'').',
   2),
  ('παρρησία', 'parrēsia', 'G3954',
   'Boldness, openness, freedom of speech, confidence; speaking without reserve or fear.',
   'From pas (all) + rhēsis (speech) — saying everything, holding nothing back. In v.4, the brothers want Jesus to act ''openly'' (en parrēsia). In v.13, no one speaks openly about Jesus ''for fear of the Jews.'' In v.26, the crowd notes that Jesus speaks boldly (parrēsia lalei). Parrēsia is a mark of the Spirit-filled church (Acts 4:13, 29, 31). The world demands boldness but punishes it; Jesus models boldness that serves truth rather than self-promotion.',
   3),
  ('διδαχή', 'didachē', 'G1322',
   'Teaching, doctrine, instruction; the content of what is taught.',
   'In v.16, ''My doctrine is not mine, but his that sent me'' (hē emē didachē ouk estin emē). In v.17, obedience to God''s will enables discernment of the doctrine''s origin. Jesus'' didachē is God''s didachē — not learned from rabbinical schools but received directly from the Father. The crowd marvels at his learning without formal education (v.15). This validates the principle that divine revelation supersedes human credentials. The test of true doctrine is not the teacher''s pedigree but the teaching''s origin.',
   4),
  ('ὕδωρ ζῶν', 'hydōr zōn', 'G5204/G2198',
   'Living water, flowing water; water that is alive, fresh, moving — as opposed to stagnant cistern water.',
   'In v.38, Jesus promises ''rivers of living water'' (potamoi hydatos zōntos). In 4:10-14, Jesus offered ''living water'' to the Samaritan woman — water springing up to eternal life. Here the promise expands: not merely a spring but rivers (potamoi — plural, abundant, overflowing). The believer becomes not just a recipient but a channel. John interprets the living water as the Holy Spirit (v.39). The imagery draws from OT promises: Ezekiel 47:1-12 (river from the temple), Zechariah 14:8 (living waters from Jerusalem), Isaiah 44:3 (water on the thirsty land).',
   5),
  ('σχίσμα', 'schisma', 'G4978',
   'Division, split, tear, schism; a separation of opinion or loyalty.',
   'From schizō (to split, tear, rend — the same verb used for the temple veil tearing, Mark 15:38). In v.43, ''there was a division among the people because of him'' (schisma egeneto di auton). The same word recurs in 9:16 and 10:19. Jesus does not bring comfortable unity but truthful division: those who receive him are separated from those who reject him. Schisma is the inevitable result of light entering darkness — not a defect of Jesus'' ministry but its necessary effect.',
   6),
  ('πνεῦμα', 'pneuma', 'G4151',
   'Spirit, breath, wind; the Holy Spirit, the third person of the Trinity.',
   'In v.39, John explains that the ''living water'' of v.38 refers to the Spirit (pneuma) which believers would receive after Jesus'' glorification. The Spirit is not yet ''given'' (oupō ēn) in the fullness of Pentecostal outpouring — not because the Spirit did not exist but because the new covenant ministry of the Spirit (permanent indwelling, John 14:16-17) awaited Christ''s completed work. The Spirit''s coming depends on Christ''s going (16:7). The Spirit glorifies Christ (16:14), applies Christ''s work, and produces Christ-like character (Galatians 5:22-23).',
   7),
  ('ὥρα', 'hōra', 'G5610',
   'Hour, time, appointed moment; the decisive moment of Jesus'' death and glorification.',
   'In v.30, ''no man laid hands on him, because his hour was not yet come'' (oupō elēlythei hē hōra autou). Hōra in John refers specifically to the appointed time of Jesus'' passion and glorification: 2:4 (''mine hour is not yet come''), 7:30 and 8:20 (''his hour was not yet come''), 12:23 (''the hour is come, that the Son of man should be glorified''), 12:27 (''Father, save me from this hour''), 13:1 (''Jesus knew that his hour was come''), 17:1 (''Father, the hour is come''). No human power can hasten or delay this divinely ordained moment.',
   8)
) AS ws(greek_word, transliteration, strongs_number, definition, word_order)
CROSS JOIN LATERAL (
  SELECT v2.id FROM verses v2
  JOIN chapters c2 ON v2.chapter_id = c2.id
  JOIN books b2 ON c2.book_id = b2.id
  WHERE b2.name = 'John' AND c2.chapter_number = 7
  AND v2.verse_number = CASE ws.word_order
    WHEN 1 THEN 2
    WHEN 2 THEN 6
    WHEN 3 THEN 26
    WHEN 4 THEN 16
    WHEN 5 THEN 38
    WHEN 6 THEN 43
    WHEN 7 THEN 39
    WHEN 8 THEN 30
  END
) v;

-- Step 4: Insert cross-references
INSERT INTO cross_references (verse_id, referenced_verse, relationship_type, note)
SELECT v.id, cr.referenced_verse, cr.relationship_type, cr.note
FROM verses v
JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  -- v.2: Feast of Tabernacles
  (2, 'Leviticus 23:33-43', 'context', 'The institution of the Feast of Tabernacles — seven days of booth-dwelling and rejoicing'),
  (2, 'Zechariah 14:16-19', 'prophecy', 'In the messianic age, all nations will celebrate the Feast of Tabernacles'),
  -- v.5: His brethren did not believe
  (5, 'Mark 3:21', 'parallel', '''He is beside himself'' — Jesus'' family thought he was out of his mind'),
  (5, 'Acts 1:14', 'thematic', 'After the resurrection, Jesus'' brothers are among the believers in the upper room'),
  (5, '1 Corinthians 15:7', 'thematic', '''Then he was seen of James'' — the resurrection converted Jesus'' brother'),
  -- v.7: The world hateth me
  (7, 'John 15:18-19', 'thematic', '''If the world hate you, ye know that it hated me before it hated you'''),
  (7, 'John 3:19-20', 'thematic', '''Men loved darkness rather than light, because their deeds were evil'''),
  -- v.17: Doing God''s will reveals truth
  (17, 'Psalm 25:14', 'thematic', '''The secret of the LORD is with them that fear him'''),
  (17, 'James 1:22', 'thematic', '''Be ye doers of the word, and not hearers only'''),
  -- v.22-23: Circumcision on the Sabbath
  (23, 'John 5:8-9, 16', 'parallel', 'The Bethesda healing on the Sabbath — the ''one work'' of v.21'),
  (23, 'Genesis 17:10-12', 'context', 'The institution of circumcision with Abraham'),
  (23, 'Leviticus 12:3', 'context', 'Circumcision on the eighth day overrides the Sabbath'),
  -- v.24: Judge righteous judgment
  (24, 'Isaiah 11:3-4', 'thematic', '''Shall not judge after the sight of his eyes... but with righteousness shall he judge the poor'''),
  (24, 'James 2:1-4', 'thematic', '''Have not the faith of our Lord Jesus Christ with respect of persons'''),
  -- v.28-29: I am from him
  (29, 'John 8:42', 'parallel', '''I proceeded forth and came from God; neither came I of myself, but he sent me'''),
  (29, 'John 16:28', 'parallel', '''I came forth from the Father, and am come into the world'''),
  -- v.30: His hour was not yet come
  (30, 'John 2:4', 'parallel', '''Mine hour is not yet come'' — Jesus'' first reference to his appointed hour'),
  (30, 'John 13:1', 'parallel', '''Jesus knew that his hour was come'' — the hour finally arrives'),
  -- v.37-38: Living water
  (37, 'Isaiah 55:1', 'thematic', '''Ho, every one that thirsteth, come ye to the waters'''),
  (37, 'Revelation 22:17', 'thematic', '''Let him that is athirst come. And whosoever will, let him take the water of life freely'''),
  (38, 'Isaiah 44:3', 'prophecy', '''I will pour water upon him that is thirsty, and floods upon the dry ground'''),
  (38, 'Ezekiel 47:1-12', 'prophecy', 'The river flowing from the temple — ever deepening, bringing life wherever it goes'),
  (38, 'Zechariah 14:8', 'prophecy', '''Living waters shall go out from Jerusalem'''),
  (38, 'John 4:14', 'parallel', '''The water that I shall give him shall be in him a well of water springing up into everlasting life'''),
  -- v.39: The Spirit
  (39, 'Acts 2:1-4', 'parallel', 'The outpouring of the Spirit at Pentecost — the fulfilment of this promise'),
  (39, 'John 16:7', 'thematic', '''If I go not away, the Comforter will not come unto you; but if I depart, I will send him'''),
  (39, 'Joel 2:28-29', 'prophecy', '''I will pour out my spirit upon all flesh'' — the Pentecost prophecy'),
  -- v.40-42: Division over identity
  (40, 'Deuteronomy 18:15', 'prophecy', '''A Prophet like unto me'' — the Prophet Moses foretold'),
  (42, 'Micah 5:2', 'prophecy', '''But thou, Bethlehem Ephratah... out of thee shall he come forth unto me that is to be ruler in Israel'''),
  (42, '2 Samuel 7:12', 'prophecy', '''I will set up thy seed after thee, which shall proceed out of thy bowels'''),
  -- v.46: Never man spake like this man
  (46, 'Matthew 7:28-29', 'parallel', '''The people were astonished at his doctrine: for he taught them as one having authority'''),
  -- v.50-51: Nicodemus
  (50, 'John 3:1-2', 'parallel', 'Nicodemus comes to Jesus by night — his first appearance'),
  (50, 'John 19:39', 'parallel', 'Nicodemus brings spices for Jesus'' burial — his final appearance, now open'),
  (51, 'Deuteronomy 1:16-17', 'context', '''Hear the causes between your brethren, and judge righteously'' — the law Nicodemus invokes'),
  -- v.52: No prophet from Galilee
  (52, '2 Kings 14:25', 'context', 'Jonah son of Amittai was from Gath-hepher in Galilee — contradicting the Pharisees'' claim')
) AS cr(verse_number, referenced_verse, relationship_type, note)
CROSS JOIN LATERAL (
  SELECT v2.id FROM verses v2
  JOIN chapters c2 ON v2.chapter_id = c2.id
  JOIN books b2 ON c2.book_id = b2.id
  WHERE b2.name = 'John' AND c2.chapter_number = 7 AND v2.verse_number = cr.verse_number
) v;
